<p><b> <i>Source</i> </b><i>: Extrapolated from Table 8 of the draft report ‘Safeguarding the benefits</i> of the ACP-EU sugar protocol in the context of the EPA negotiations’ (February 20th 2007)</p><p> As can be seen from the table above, while all but St Kitts &amp; Nevis and Trinidad &amp; Tobago can profitably export at the pre-reform EU sugar price, at the post-reform price which will prevail from 2009/10, even with successful restructuring as currently envisaged, sugar exports to the EU market will be unprofitable for, Kenya, Madagascar, Côte d’Ivoire, Barbados, marginal for Tanzania, Congo, Jamaica and substantially less profitable for Belize, Mauritius and Fiji. The only sugar-protocol beneficiaries comfortably able to supply the EU market with sugar at the post-reform 2009/10 prices will be Malawi, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Swaziland, Mozambique and Guyana. </p><p> However, if as is feared, as part of the 2013 round of CAP reforms, the EC introduces a further round of reductions in the sugar price, comparable to those introduced in other arable sectors (i.e. bringing EU prices down to 50% of the pre-reform level, a level which would still leave prices approximately 50% above current world market price levels – depending on the euro/US dollar exchange rate) then sugar exports would remain clearly profitable only for Malawi, Zimbabwe and Mozambique, with exports of sugar from Swaziland and Zambia being marginal, and exports from Guyana being non-viable.</p><p> It is this underlying economic reality which is causing such concern among ACP sugar-protocol beneficiaries.</p><p> Against this background, it should be noted that while the EC is dismantling guaranteed prices for EU sugar farmers, it is still maintaining a ‘guaranteed’ income via the incorporation of the sugar sector into the single-payment scheme for EU farmers, a scheme which in the cereals sector (where CAP reform is most advanced) now delivers between 57% and 70% of the total income of EU cereal farmers, making them much less dependent on the prices received in the market place for their overall economic well-being. </p>
		</div>
		
